	affiliations = {Dep. of Plant Sciences, Univ. of California, One Shields Ave., Davis, 95616, CA, United States; USDA-ARS, Delta Water Management Research Unit, 504 University Loop East, Jonesboro, 72401, AR, United States; PO Box 571, 17 Jill Lane, Casscoe, 72026, AR, United States; Louisiana State Univ. Agricultural Center, H. Rouse Caffey Rice Research Station, 1373 Caffey Rd., Rayne, 70578, LA, United States; Biological and Agricultural Engineering, Univ. of Arkansas, 231 ENGR Hall, Fayetteville, 72701, AR, United States; Texas AandM AgriLife Research Center, 1509 Aggie Dr., Beaumont, 77713, TX, United States; Field to Market, 777 N. Capitol St., NE Suite 803, Washington, 20002, DC, United States},
	abstract = {Previous reviews have quantified factors affecting greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions from Asian rice (Oryza sativa L.) systems, but not from rice systems typical for the United States, which often vary considerably particularly in practices (i.e., water and carbon management) that affect emissions. Using meta-analytic and regression approaches, existing data from the United States were examined to quantify GHG emissions and major practices affecting emissions. Due to different production practices, major rice production regions were defined as the mid-South (Arkansas, Texas, Louisiana, Mississippi, and Missouri) and California, with emissions being evaluated separately. Average growing season CH<sub>4</sub> emissions for the mid-South and California were 194 (95% confidence interval [CI] = 129-260) and 218 kg CH<sub>4</sub> ha<sup>-1</sup> season<sup>-1</sup> (95% CI = 153-284), respectively. Growing season N<sub>2</sub>O emissions were similar between regions (0.14 kg N<sub>2</sub>O ha<sup>-1</sup> season<sup>-1</sup>). Ratoon cropping (allowing an additional harvestable crop to grow from stubble after the initial harvest), common along the Gulf Coast of the mid-South, had average CH<sub>4</sub> emissions of 540 kg CH<sub>4</sub> ha<sup>-1</sup> season<sup>-1</sup> (95% CI = 465-614). Water and residue management practices such as alternate wetting and drying, and stand establishment method (water vs. dry seeding), and the amount of residue from the previous crop had the largest effect on growing season CH<sub>4</sub> emissions. However, soil texture, sulfate additions, and cultivar selection also affected growing season CH<sub>4</sub> emissions. This analysis can be used for the development of tools to estimate and mitigate GHG emissions from US rice systems and other similarly mechanized systems in temperate regions. © American Society of Agronomy, Crop Science Society of America, and Soil Science Society of America.},
	keywords = {Agriculture; Arkansas; California; Greenhouse Effect; Greenhouse Gases; Methane; Mississippi; Oryza; Texas; Crops; Gas emissions; Sulfur compounds; methane; nitrogen oxide; nitrous oxide; organic matter; sulfate; Confidence interval; Cultivar selection; Management practices; Mechanized systems; Production practice; Rice (Oryza sativa L.); Stand establishment; WETTING AND DRYING; Article; carbon footprint; controlled study; crop; cultivar; decomposition; grain yield; harvest; nonhuman; rice; soil texture; United States; water management; agriculture; analysis; Arkansas; California; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; Mississippi; Oryza; Texas; Greenhouse gases},
