	abstract = {Comparative effects of reputable growth media, organic compost (ORS), and rice husk biochar (RIFORB) on Chlorophytum comosum captured a distinctive factor engendering resilience to neglect. C. comosum grown in various blends of compost and biochar was vulnerable, except in the case of 100 % biochar and 100 % compost. C. comosum grown in biochar developed extended roots and remained green despite the water deficit, fortification-free, and soil-less conditions. A distinct nanoscale root system, characterized by arrays of 50 nm-width strings, unreeled from 100 to 200 µm-length ‘flaps’ as a high-precision navigator. Extra-high-resolution Field Emission Scanning Electron Microscopy revealed the nano strings weaving through the pyrogenic nanopores of the RIFORB, giving rise to mineral anchoring. The nanoscale response to the pyrolyzed structure marks a novel pyrogenic minero-tropism, reciprocating with the nanostructured material of dissolved minerals for survival. Not triggered by ORS, the adaptive phenomenon signals the potential of RIFORB for high-resilience and high-precision soil-less farming with a low water footprint. © 2025},
