	affiliations = {Department of Field Crops, Faculty of Agriculture, University of Erciyes, Kayseri, 38000, Türkiye; Department of Field Crops, Faculty of Agriculture, Bilecik Seyh Edebali University, Bilecik, 11000, Türkiye; Department of Biosystems Engineering, Faculty of Agriculture, University of Erciyes, Kayseri, 38000, Türkiye; Department of Agricultural Structures and Irrigation, Faculty of Agriculture, Canakkale Onsekiz Mart University, Canakkale, 17000, Türkiye; Department of Field Crops, Institute of Natural and Applied Sciences, Canakkale Onsekiz Mart University, Canakkale, 17020, Türkiye; Lapseki Vocational College, Canakkale Onsekiz Mart University, Canakkale, 17000, Türkiye; Department of Agricultural Biotechnology, Faculty of Agriculture, University of Erciyes, Kayseri, 13000, Türkiye; Department of Field Crops, Faculty of Agriculture, Canakkale Onsekiz Mart University, Canakkale, 17100, Türkiye},
	abstract = {Rice serves as the primary food source for the majority of the world’s population. In terms of irrigation water, the highest volume of irrigation water is utilized in paddy irrigation. Excessive water use causes both waste of limited water resources and various environmental problems. The drip irrigation method with high water use efficiency will reduce both the need for irrigation water and the environmental footprint of paddy production. This study was conducted to investigate the effects of two different irrigation intervals (2 and 4 days) and four irrigation levels (150%, 125%, 100%, and 75% of evaporation from a Class-A pan) on the nutritional traits of three different paddy cultivars (Ronaldo, Baldo, and Osmancık). Increasing irrigation intervals and decreasing irrigation levels reduced the nutritional properties (protein, oil, starch) of the rice grains. In addition, increasing irrigation levels also increased the phytic acid and dietary fiber contents. The highest protein (7.14%) and total starch (87.10%) contents were obtained from the 150% irrigation treatments. The highest amylose content (20.74%) was obtained from the 75% irrigation treatment. In general, it was found that irrigation levels should be applied at 125% and 150% to increase the mineral content of rice grains. Although water deficits decreased the nutritional properties of the paddy cultivars, drip irrigation at an appropriate level did not have any negative effects on nutritional traits. © 2025 by the authors.},
